I'm using Trac backed by PostgreSQL DB. In order to keep my DB clean and not interfere with other applications' tables I set up Trac to create all its tables in a specific schema ("trac"). The default "public" schema is empty.

In My config/trac.ini I have following DB URL:
[trac]
database = postgres://user:password@localhost:5432/trac_db?schema=trac

When importing this Trac database to JIRA there was following message in step called "Map fields" (the one right after "Map custom fields"):

Unexpected exception: ERROR: relation "ticket" does not exist

An error occurred whilst rendering this message. Please contact the administrators, and inform them of this bug. Details: ------- org.apache.velocity.exception.MethodInvocationException: Invocation of method 'getValueCountForField' in class com.atlassian.jira.plugins.importer.imports.config.ValueMappingHelperImpl threw exception java.lang.NullPointerException at com.atlassian.jira.plugins.jira-importers-plugin:actions//templates/admin/views/common/importerFieldMappingsPage.vm[line 25, column 60] at
... (a very long stack trace)

I managed to come up with 2 workarounds:

1) Create alias-views for trac.* tables in "puclic" schema:
create view attachment        as select * from trac.attachment       ;
create view auth_cookie       as select * from trac.auth_cookie      ;
create view cache             as select * from trac.cache            ;
create view component         as select * from trac.component        ;
create view enum              as select * from trac.enum             ;
create view milestone         as select * from trac.milestone        ;
create view node_change       as select * from trac.node_change      ;
create view permission        as select * from trac.permission       ;
create view report            as select * from trac.report           ;
create view report_id_seq     as select * from trac.report_id_seq    ;
create view repository        as select * from trac.repository       ;
create view revision          as select * from trac.revision         ;
create view session           as select * from trac.session          ;
create view session_attribute as select * from trac.session_attribute;
create view system            as select * from trac.system           ;
create view ticket            as select * from trac.ticket           ;
create view ticket_change     as select * from trac.ticket_change    ;
create view ticket_custom     as select * from trac.ticket_custom    ;
create view ticket_id_seq     as select * from trac.ticket_id_seq    ;
create view version           as select * from trac.version          ;
create view wiki              as select * from trac.wiki             ;

2) Extend search path of this DB by adding "trac" schema:
ALTER DATABASE trac_db SET search_path = "$user",public,trac;
*and* starting import procedure from scratch (hitting browser's BACK + pressing NEXT didn't work - probably DB connection is kept open in some pool during entire import transaction).

With any of these workarounds import process was finished smoothly. However it would bee cool if importer plugin respected "schema=trac" parameter when present in DB URL.

